statement:
Use the trapezoidal rule with $n = 3$ to approximate

\begin{align*}\displaystyle
\int_{-2}^{4}\frac{dx}{1 + \left(\frac{x}{2}\right)^{4}}\end{align*}

sols:
As the hint suggests, we should calculate all the information we need to
begin. First, we find the width of the intervals:

\begin{align*}\Delta x = \frac{b - a}{n} = \frac{4 - (-2)}{3} = 2.\end{align*} We also need
the endpoints of the intervals:

\begin{align*}x_k = \displaystyle a + k\Delta x,\end{align*} for k = 0 to k = 3. Thus the
points are -2, 0, 2, and 4. Then the formula for the Trapezoidal rule is

\begin{align*}T_n = \frac{\Delta x}{2} (f(x_0) + 2f(x_1) + 2f(x_2) + ... + 2f(x_{n-1}) + f(x_n)),\end{align*}
so we can fill in our information:

\begin{align*}T_3 = \frac{2}{2} \left(\frac{1}{1 + \left(\frac{-2}{2}\right)^{4}} + 2\frac{1}{1 + \left(\frac{0}{2}\right)^{4}} + 2\frac{1}{1 + \left(\frac{2}{2}\right)^{4}} + \frac{1}{1 + \left(\frac{4}{2}\right)^{4}}\right),\end{align*}

\begin{align*}T_3 = \frac{1}{1 + 1} + 2\frac{1}{1 + 0} + 2\frac{1}{1 + 1} + \frac{1}{1 + 16},\end{align*}

\begin{align*}T_3 = \frac{1}{2} + 2 + 1 + \frac{1}{17},\end{align*}

\begin{align*}T_3 = \frac{121}{34} \approx 3.5588.\end{align*}

Notice if we actually evaluate the integral,

\begin{align*}\int_{-2}^4\frac{1}{1+\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)^4}\textrm{d}x=3.8742\end{align*}

so we see that the trapezoidal rule with only 4 points is already in
fairly good agreement.
